“The fascinating lore of wine and its pleasures, commentaries by cele- brities and connoisseurs, plus simul- taneous screening by some 160 TY stations across the country, made the first national television program on wine a milestone event. Produced by National Educational Television (N.E.T.), the hour-long program was telecast in prime eve- ning time as an absorbing version of the ‘Your Money’s Worth’ show. It sought to remove some of the ‘mys- tery’ and ‘snobbery’ that often sur- rounds wine and to demonstrate that buying wine can be as practical a matter as the purchase of any other commodity.

Burgess Meredith, actor- director and connoisseur, tests a wine during the na- tional Educational Tele- vision’s consumer series

Featured in this full-color program were celebrity-actor-director Bur- gess Meredith; Episcopal priest- gourmet-author Father Robert Capon; and wine sipper and world- wide wine authority Peter Sichel; all of whom gave their views on the various characteristics and costs of wines and participated in a blind tasting.

Well known wine and spirits retailer Sam Aaron, president of New York’s Sherry-Lehmann, Inc. gave some very practical advice on starting a $50 wine cellar.

Commentaries included both Ameri- can and imported wine types. Among interesting points was an explana- tion by Burgess Meredith on how to taste wine properly—smell for bou- quet, hold to light for color, put a tiny bit of wine under the tongue and breathe. (The taste, Mr. Sichel commented, will continue to be with you for a number of seconds, or will stop suddenly—the length of time refiects the greatness of the wine. ) Sherry-Lehmann’s Sam Aaron spoke on the value of vintage charts as general guides but cautioned against taking them too literally. He pointed out that great vineyards have pro- duced poor wines during great years and extraordinary wines during a poor year. He also urged budding wine devotees to ‘adventure among the vineyards of the world,’ to try a great variety of wines whether they be from California, New York, France, Spain, Portugal, Germany, Israel, Australia or wine-producing countries of South America. ‘It’s not enough to just find a wine you like and repeat yourself ad infinitum,’ he said.
